               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-691" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-691" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-691" type="surname" value="LIDDIARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-691" type="given" value="GILBERT"></interp>GILBERT LIDDIARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a manufacturing chemist, and live at Step<lb></lb>ney. On the 4th of November, I was with my clerk in my garden—the barking of a dog attracted our attention—we went into the shrubbery, and saw a bundle of clothes—my clerk seized the prisoner about two yards from the bundle—I asked him how he came there, and whether he had stolen the clothes—he gave no reason for being there—I took hold of him, and he said, "Give me my waistcoat"—we took the bundle, and the waistcoat was near them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341124-name-692" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-692" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-692" type="surname" value="DAVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341124-name-692" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>FRANCIS DAVIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Liddiard. I took hold of the pri<lb></lb>soner—he was crawling away on all fours about two yards from the bundle—I found his waistcoat on the spot where I had taken the bundle, with some other clothes—it was about half-past seven o'clock.</p>
